WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.410 --> 00:00:04.710
- [Ian] Clay is the
perfect material, really.

00:00:04.710 --> 00:00:06.000
- [Sean] If you think
about Grommet, you know,

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:08.340
all the emotion in that face comes

00:00:08.340 --> 00:00:09.930
from a movement of the brow.

00:00:09.930 --> 00:00:11.250
- Wallace is is kind of classic.

00:00:11.250 --> 00:00:12.180
- Cheese.

00:00:12.180 --> 00:00:15.060
- Clay underpins really who
we are and what we're about.

00:00:15.060 --> 00:00:16.980
Aardman started with "Chicken Run,"

00:00:16.980 --> 00:00:18.940
we're about to release our 11th movie

00:00:20.220 --> 00:00:23.160
- [Ian] You need this
very specific particular

00:00:23.160 --> 00:00:25.680
type of clay to be able to do what we do.

00:00:25.680 --> 00:00:26.700
- [Kate] Well for many years,

00:00:26.700 --> 00:00:28.590
Aardman has used a type of clay

00:00:28.590 --> 00:00:31.170
manufactured by a company called Newplast.

00:00:31.170 --> 00:00:33.000
- I think we used that over 25 years,

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:34.650
that was the only company doing it.

00:00:34.650 --> 00:00:38.010
- The founders of Newplast
had decided, rightly so,

00:00:38.010 --> 00:00:40.380
they wanted to retire and move on.

00:00:40.380 --> 00:00:41.520
- [Ian] You sort of suddenly realized,

00:00:41.520 --> 00:00:43.110
well there's no other product out there.

00:00:43.110 --> 00:00:46.560
So then you did start to
wonder, well, what will happen

00:00:46.560 --> 00:00:49.410
when we sort of finally use
up everything we've got here.

00:00:54.952 --> 00:00:55.785
- We've got loads of clay
here, we've got so much now,

00:00:55.785 --> 00:00:58.260
is I've got so many hidey holes of clay,

00:00:58.260 --> 00:01:00.660
so I've got about three or
four rooms of shelves full

00:01:00.660 --> 00:01:03.270
of clay actually, and
this is a terracotta,

00:01:03.270 --> 00:01:05.643
which actually famously we use for Morph.

00:01:06.540 --> 00:01:08.370
- [Ian] We don't have any wax in our clay.

00:01:08.370 --> 00:01:10.650
A lot of time it like the
wax, especially in the heat

00:01:10.650 --> 00:01:11.760
and the lights, it will melt

00:01:11.760 --> 00:01:13.320
and it will go soft and it will droop.

00:01:13.320 --> 00:01:15.000
We can't have like a grommet

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:19.290
or Morph just suddenly
collapsing over several hours.

00:01:19.290 --> 00:01:22.770
- It's incredibly important
that we get the clay right

00:01:22.770 --> 00:01:25.830
because it can really slow down animation.

00:01:25.830 --> 00:01:28.770
So one day I'd got an email from our CEO,

00:01:28.770 --> 00:01:30.660
which I thought was a bit unusual

00:01:30.660 --> 00:01:34.980
and essentially he was
messaging me to say, did I know

00:01:34.980 --> 00:01:37.886
that Newplast that the company

00:01:37.886 --> 00:01:40.410
was in danger of closing down.

00:01:40.410 --> 00:01:42.510
I was in shock a bit, really.

00:01:42.510 --> 00:01:45.510
- It took me a bit by surprise

00:01:45.510 --> 00:01:49.500
in how quickly it became a
story all over the world.

00:01:49.500 --> 00:01:50.760
- [Reporter] Aardman Animations,

00:01:50.760 --> 00:01:54.990
the legendary stop motion studio
is apparently out of clay.

00:01:54.990 --> 00:01:56.610
- [Reporter 2] Creators
of Wallace and Grommet

00:01:56.610 --> 00:01:58.050
are headed for disaster.

00:01:58.050 --> 00:02:00.234
- It's funny as well because I remember

00:02:00.234 --> 00:02:04.200
my father-in-law even he
looked horrified asking

00:02:04.200 --> 00:02:05.370
me, what are you gonna do?

00:02:05.370 --> 00:02:06.660
You're not gonna be able to work.

00:02:06.660 --> 00:02:09.810
- My first thought was, what
stock have we got in house

00:02:09.810 --> 00:02:11.460
for Wallace and Grommet?

00:02:11.460 --> 00:02:12.570
- I always keep a certain amount of stock

00:02:12.570 --> 00:02:14.160
anyway, we were never gonna run out,

00:02:14.160 --> 00:02:15.150
well not for years.

00:02:15.150 --> 00:02:16.770
- So I knew it wasn't a problem,

00:02:16.770 --> 00:02:18.840
although at some point
clearly it was gonna

00:02:18.840 --> 00:02:20.130
become a problem.

00:02:20.130 --> 00:02:23.310
- Luckily we had just made
a big order from Newplast

00:02:23.310 --> 00:02:26.370
and so we thought, okay,
right, we know we are all right

00:02:26.370 --> 00:02:27.930
for this project.

00:02:27.930 --> 00:02:30.060
We started scouring the kind of shops

00:02:30.060 --> 00:02:33.423
and warehouses just to kind
of add to the stockpile.

00:02:35.730 --> 00:02:39.420
We decided right, okay, we are
going to at least have a try.

00:02:39.420 --> 00:02:41.463
Can we mix clay ourselves?

00:02:44.460 --> 00:02:47.310
- In charge of producing
most of the clay we do here

00:02:47.310 --> 00:02:49.083
and matching color.

00:02:50.603 --> 00:02:51.450
Out and in, out and in.

00:02:51.450 --> 00:02:52.830
So that can go on for hours and hours.

00:02:52.830 --> 00:02:54.480
So that can be quite demanding.

00:02:54.480 --> 00:02:56.187
But it's quite nice to
see like the color you,

00:02:56.187 --> 00:02:58.410
you get your white, you
get your, your reds,

00:02:58.410 --> 00:03:00.150
you get your pinks and
maybe a bit of yellow

00:03:00.150 --> 00:03:02.654
and then you know, you put it all together

00:03:02.654 --> 00:03:04.500
and within a few hours you've got Wallace.

00:03:04.500 --> 00:03:06.120
It's quite satisfying to see actually.

00:03:06.120 --> 00:03:08.460
You wanna want to kind of like,

00:03:08.460 --> 00:03:10.530
the test is normally
just to kind of see like,

00:03:10.530 --> 00:03:12.180
does it stick to itself?

00:03:12.180 --> 00:03:13.230
Like you gotta play it by ear.

00:03:13.230 --> 00:03:14.460
That's why it's really hard.

00:03:14.460 --> 00:03:15.570
It's no set rules really.

00:03:15.570 --> 00:03:17.320
You've just, a lot of it's by feel.

00:03:18.180 --> 00:03:21.000
I've been doing it so long
now, I'll know like, right,

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:22.530
this is, well this is too soft.

00:03:22.530 --> 00:03:25.603
This will need five, six, 7% chalk.

00:03:27.060 --> 00:03:28.830
- Eventually we did make something,

00:03:28.830 --> 00:03:31.620
which I would say it definitely was clay.

00:03:31.620 --> 00:03:35.670
We thought, well we don't really
want to go into production

00:03:35.670 --> 00:03:37.110
because that's not what we do.

00:03:37.110 --> 00:03:40.290
You know, we make puppets and we animate.

00:03:40.290 --> 00:03:42.330
- This is Feathers.

00:03:42.330 --> 00:03:45.690
Originally we had a
clay glove on his head.

00:03:45.690 --> 00:03:49.740
Now this is actually
silicon just for ease.

00:03:49.740 --> 00:03:50.640
- Good grief.

00:03:50.640 --> 00:03:54.210
- [Ian] All the black part of him is clay.

00:03:54.210 --> 00:03:58.290
This is a solid chest and
then he's got rubber legs

00:03:58.290 --> 00:04:01.440
and a solid beak and a
couple of glass pinheads

00:04:01.440 --> 00:04:03.060
that go in for his eyes.

00:04:03.060 --> 00:04:04.680
When you're animating him,

00:04:04.680 --> 00:04:07.380
you're just moving it
obviously bit by bit,

00:04:07.380 --> 00:04:09.930
but you can see up here, it all starts

00:04:09.930 --> 00:04:11.730
to crack as soon as you've moved it.

00:04:11.730 --> 00:04:14.250
I would be constantly going in

00:04:14.250 --> 00:04:17.070
and kind of smoothing this area down

00:04:17.070 --> 00:04:19.140
to get it back into shape.

00:04:19.140 --> 00:04:21.093
- But you are supposed to be locked up.

00:04:21.960 --> 00:04:26.960
- We do think of ourselves as
performers, much like actors.

00:04:26.970 --> 00:04:29.940
You can get really nuanced performance

00:04:29.940 --> 00:04:33.780
and you have a way bigger
range of subtlety using clay.

00:04:34.950 --> 00:04:38.010
- We aren't actually
using enormous quantities

00:04:38.010 --> 00:04:39.360
of clay these days.

00:04:39.360 --> 00:04:43.360
Maybe at the beginning of a
feature film we will buy like 30

00:04:43.360 --> 00:04:46.290
to 40 kilos, which doesn't
really sound that much,

00:04:46.290 --> 00:04:49.140
but we try to kind of
be fairly conservative

00:04:49.140 --> 00:04:52.140
with the way we use it and
not waste a load of it.

00:04:52.140 --> 00:04:54.090
- I mean we've still got a hundred

00:04:54.090 --> 00:04:55.680
or so several hundred boxes now,

00:04:55.680 --> 00:04:57.840
so we're still good now really actually.

00:04:57.840 --> 00:04:59.700
- And then Hue came along.

00:04:59.700 --> 00:05:04.230
They do a lot of packages
and, and products for schools

00:05:04.230 --> 00:05:07.740
and for students and
decided to buy Newplast.

00:05:07.740 --> 00:05:10.890
- Suddenly it felt like there
was this lifeline out there

00:05:10.890 --> 00:05:15.265
for this very specific,
particular type of clay.

00:05:15.265 --> 00:05:16.465
- We were very relieved.

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:20.040
- There was a period where
we were really smoothing

00:05:20.040 --> 00:05:22.410
everything down, but we found it was kind

00:05:22.410 --> 00:05:23.820
of smoothing all the work out of it

00:05:23.820 --> 00:05:25.020
and all the life out of it.

00:05:25.020 --> 00:05:26.880
So over the recent years,

00:05:26.880 --> 00:05:29.010
we've really made a conscious effort to

00:05:29.010 --> 00:05:31.770
put back in those fingerprints

00:05:31.770 --> 00:05:34.290
because obviously isn't
an unanimous character.

00:05:34.290 --> 00:05:37.890
It's funny how you can just by touching it

00:05:37.890 --> 00:05:41.040
and moving it, it's not breathing

00:05:41.040 --> 00:05:43.533
but it's, it's kind of living.

00:05:44.610 --> 00:05:47.310
- It's all about the soul,
about the human input

00:05:47.310 --> 00:05:50.850
and I really don't understand
why you would want to kind

00:05:50.850 --> 00:05:52.350
of have a machine to do that.

00:05:52.350 --> 00:05:55.380
There's always going to
be something lacking that

00:05:55.380 --> 00:05:58.140
to me it can only ever just be okay.

00:05:58.140 --> 00:06:01.020
- I think clay is a medium
that's defined a studio.

00:06:01.020 --> 00:06:02.880
You know, we're in our 50th year,

00:06:02.880 --> 00:06:04.878
we are the best in the world at it

00:06:04.878 --> 00:06:07.078
and we'll be using it
for the next 50 years.

